INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:Detected 9 issues:
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [4] missing_autotune: The Model forward path calls attn_fwd_launch(), which launches _attn_fwd with hardcoded BLOCK_M=128, BLOCK_N=64, num_warps=16, num_stages=3. Although an autotune config list and tuner are defined, they are not used by attn_fwd_launch() or Model.forward(). For the target shape N_CTX=16384, HEAD_DIM=128 on Intel XPU, the optimal BLOCK_N/BLOCK_M/warps can vary significantly.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] suboptimal_autotune_configs: The existing forward autotune configs only try BLOCK_N in {32,64}. For HEAD_DIM=128 and very long sequence length, BLOCK_N=128 is often an important candidate because it halves the number of K/V loop iterations versus BLOCK_N=64. The current configs may miss better XPU DPA utilization and lower loop overhead.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] suboptimal_warps: The active forward launch uses num_warps=16. For large attention tiles on Intel Data Center GPU Max, 32 warps is often beneficial, especially with grf_mode='256' and HEAD_DIM=128. The autotune configs include 32 warps, but the Model path never uses them.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] no_swizzling: For N_CTX > 512 the grid is ordered as (Z, H, num_blocks_m). This tends to schedule different heads before adjacent M-blocks of the same head. Since every Q block for a given head streams the same K/V sequence, scheduling adjacent M blocks of the same head closer together can improve L2 reuse of K/V tiles.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] unnecessary_materialization: The inference-only Model.forward path returns only O, but attn_fwd_launch() still allocates M and _attn_fwd stores the per-row log-sum-exp values to M. This M tensor is only needed for backward; in the provided Model path it is immediately discarded.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [4] unnecessary_materialization: The backward path materializes a full scaled copy of K with arg_k = arg_k * (ctx.sm_scale * RCP_LN2) before launching _attn_bwd. This creates an extra PyTorch elementwise kernel, allocates another K-sized tensor, writes it to HBM, and then _attn_bwd reads it back.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [4] non_contiguous_input: The forward kernel constructs tensor descriptors assuming Q/K/V/O are contiguous with flattened strides [HEAD_DIM,1], but attn_fwd_launch() and Model.forward() do not enforce contiguity. Non-contiguous inputs would either produce wrong addressing or very poor memory access behavior.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] manual_pointer_arithmetic: Several backward/preprocess loads and stores use manual pointer arithmetic for 2D blocks even though other parts of the code already use tensor descriptors. Manual arithmetic is more error-prone and misses automatic boundary handling / descriptor optimizations.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] missing_boundary_check: The forward and backward kernels generally assume N_CTX is divisible by BLOCK_M/BLOCK_N and HEAD_DIM matches the tile. The target N_CTX=16384,D=128 is divisible, but the wrapper uses cdiv() in forward without masks or descriptor boundary_check, so other sequence lengths would read/write out of bounds.
